            <div class="highlight">
                Originally built in 1636, the bridge was historically reserved for imperial messengers and Toshogu shrine priests only.
            </div>

<p>The current bridge, rebuilt in 1907, stands 28 meters long and 7.4 meters wide. Its distinctive red lacquer finish and elegant arch design make it a symbol of Nikko itself. The bridge connects the secular and sacred worlds, marking your transition into the UNESCO World Heritage site.</p>

<p>Legend says that the Buddhist monk Shodo Shonin was helped across the raging river here by two serpents, allowing him to establish temples in the area over 1,200 years ago.</p>

